To work with both your personal repository and the team repository while pushing to both, follow these steps:

1. Clone Your Personal Repository
First, ensure you have your personal repository cloned locally:

git clone <your-personal-repo-url>
cd <repository-folder>

2. Add the Team Repository as a Remote
Now add the team repository as a second remote:


git remote add team <team-repository-url>


git pull personal master --allow-unrelated-histories

You can rename the remotes branches:
git remote rename origin team
and the local branches:
git checkout <old-branch-name>
git branch -m <new-branch-name>
If the branch is tracked by a remote branch
git push origin --delete <old-branch-name>
git push origin -u <new-branch-name>

Example
To rename a branch called feature1 to feature-enhanced:
git checkout feature1
git branch -m feature-enhanced
git push origin --delete feature1
git push origin -u feature-enhanced

3. Verify Both Remotes
Check the remotes to confirm both personal and team repositories are set up:

git remote -v
You should see something like this:

origin  <your-personal-repo-url> (fetch)
origin  <your-personal-repo-url> (push)
team    <team-repository-url> (fetch)
team    <team-repository-url> (push)

4. Push to Both Repositories
You can push your changes to both repositories manually or use a convenience alias.

Push Manually
Push to your personal repository:

git push origin <branch-name>

Push to the team repository:

git push team <branch-name>

OPTIONAL
Automate with an Alias
Create an alias to push to both repositories at once:

git config --global alias.pushboth '!git push origin && git push team'
Now you can push to both repositories with:

git pushboth

5. Work with the Repositories
When you pull, decide which repository to pull from:

Pull from your personal repository:

git pull origin <branch-name>

git pull team <branch-name>

You can work with branches as usual, and changes will propagate to both repositories when you push.

6. Ensure Authentication
Make sure your SSH keys or credentials are configured for both repositories to avoid authentication issues. For example:

Use SSH for both repositories, or
Set up HTTPS credentials caching if using HTTPS.
